final dataset

Since missing values in Yearbulit and Buildingarea are so large, it is decided to remove these 2 attrbiutes directly, while missing values in car is relatively small, we cleaned all rows with missing values in car. and the final data contains 13518 rows with 19 attributes.

data = data%>%select(Suburb,Address,Rooms,Type,Price,Method,SellerG,Date,Distance,Postcode,Bedroom2,Bathroom,Car,Landsize,CouncilArea,Lattitude,Longtitude,Regionname,Propertycount)
data = na.omit(data)

distribution of house price

library(ggplot2)
x <- data$Price 
dens = density(x)
h<-hist(x, freq = FALSE, ylim = c(0,max(dens$y)),breaks=35, col="lightblue", xlab="price", main="Histogram of price") 

lines(dens, col="blue", lwd=2)
abline(v = mean(data$Price), lwd = 2, col = "red") 

summary(data$Price)

normalisation applied to house price

price1  = log(data$Price)
x <- price1 
dens = density(price1)
h<-hist(x, freq = FALSE, ylim = c(0,max(dens$y)),breaks=35, col="lightblue", xlab="log(price)", main="Histogram of log(price)") 
lines(dens, col="blue", lwd=2) 
abline(v = mean(price1), lwd = 2, col = "red")

categorical transformed to numerical variables.

data2 = data%>%select(Rooms,Price,Distance,Bedroom2,Bathroom,Car,Lattitude,Longtitude,Propertycount,Postcode,Type,Suburb,Method,SellerG,CouncilArea,Regionname,Landsize)
data2$Type <- as.numeric(as.factor(data2$Type))
data2$Suburb <-as.numeric(as.factor(data2$Suburb))
data2$Method <- as.numeric(as.factor(data2$Method))
data2$SellerG <- as.numeric(as.factor(data2$SellerG))
data2$CouncilArea <- as.numeric(as.factor(data2$CouncilArea))
data2$Regionname <- as.numeric(as.factor(data2$Regionname))
